    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-01-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-01-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="365"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                <head>365. Memorandum From President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="from"
                        >Kennedy</persName> to the Director of the Office of Emergency Planning
                        (<persName corresp="#p_MDEA1" type="to">McDermott</persName>)<note n="0"
                        type="source" xml:id="d365fn0">Source: Washington National Records Center,
                            <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 40, Department of Commerce, Executive
                        Secretariat Files: <gloss target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 69 A 6828, Office of
                        the Secretary, President’s Committee on Stockpiling. No classification
                        marking. Transmitted with a February 6 covering letter from McDermott to
                        Secretary of Commerce <persName corresp="#p_HLH1">Luther H.
                            Hodges</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-01-30">January 30, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have reviewed the report of the Executive Stockpile Committee on “Disposing of
                    Excess Stockpile Materials,”<note n="1" xml:id="d365fn1">
                        <ref target="#d364">Document 364</ref>.</note> and I approve Recommendations
                    Nos. 1 through 14.</p>
                <p>Although we should maintain an adequate stockpile of strategic materials, we
                    should dispose of the materials that are in excess of our needs. Such disposals
                    should be made in the light of our national interest and our desire to avoid any
                    serious disruption of the markets. The development of long-range disposal
                    policies and plans should proceed in anticipation of enabling legislation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">
                            <hi rend="strong">John Kennedy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
